TITLE: Normalizing Selector Arguments in WordPress Data (JavaScript)
DESCRIPTION: This snippet illustrates the importance of argument normalization in selector calls to ensure consistent resolution status. The use of a normalization method is demonstrated to convert arguments to the expected types.
SOURCE: https://github.com/wordpress/gutenberg/blob/trunk/packages/data/README.md#2025-04-21_snippet_21

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
const getItemsSelector = ( name, type, id ) => {
	return state.items[ name ][ type ][ id ] || null;
};

// Define normalization method.
getItemsSelector.__unstableNormalizeArgs = ( args ) => {
	// "id" argument at the 2nd index
	if (args[2] && typeof args[2] === 'string' ) {
		args[2] === Number(args[2]);
	}

	return args;
};

// Call with correct number type.
registry.select( 'store' ).getItems( 'foo', 'bar', 54 );

// Call with the wrong string type, **but** here we have avoided an
// wanted resolver call because '54' is guaranteed to have been
// coerced to a number by the `__unstableNormalizeArgs` method.
registry.select( 'store' ).getItems( 'foo', 'bar', '54' );
```

